# Create Pull Request

Create a pull request using the team template and GitHub CLI.

## Instructions

You are creating a pull request. Follow these steps:

### 1. Initial analysis
- Run `git status` and `git diff` to inspect current branch changes.
- Check whether the current branch tracks a remote branch and whether it needs to be pushed.
- Run `git log` and `git diff [base-branch]...HEAD` to understand all commits in this branch.
- Analyze ALL changes before writing the PR description.

### 2. Preparation
- Push the current branch to remote if needed.
- For a new branch, use: `git push -u origin <branch-name>`.

### 3. PR template
Create the PR using the following template:

```markdown
## Description
<!-- Provide a clear and concise description of what this PR does -->
[INSERT DESCRIPTION HERE]

## Type of Change
<!-- Check the relevant option(s) -->
- [ ] Bug fix (non-breaking change which fixes an issue)
- [ ] New feature (non-breaking change which adds functionality)
- [ ] Breaking change (fix or feature that would cause existing functionality to fail)
- [ ] Documentation update
- [ ] Refactor (no functional changes)
- [ ] Performance improvement
- [ ] Dependency update

## Changes Made
<!-- List key changes in this PR -->
-
-
-

## How to Test
<!-- Describe how to validate the changes -->
1.
2.
3.

## Related Issues
<!-- Link related issues using #number -->
Fixes #
Related to #

## Checklist
- [ ] Tests were added/updated
- [ ] Documentation was updated
- [ ] Code follows project standards
- [ ] Changes were tested locally
```

### 4. Create PR via GitHub CLI
- Use `gh pr create` with title and body based on the template above.
- Ensure the PR body is complete and actionable.
- Return the PR URL after creation.

## Important notes
- Keep the PR focused and avoid unrelated changes.
- If there are multiple unrelated commit groups, ask whether to split into separate PRs.
- Prefer clear, review-friendly language and explicit test steps.
